SIMPLE: there
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: There
<hw>There</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>ther</ets>,
AS. <ets>⟦edh⟧⟦aemac⟧r</ets>; akin to D. <ets>daar</ets>, G.
<ets>da</ets>, OHG. <ets>d⟦amac⟧r</ets>, Sw. & Dan. <ets>der</ets>,
Icel. & Goth. <ets>⟦thorn⟧ar</ets>, Skr. <ets>tarhi</ets> then, and E.
<ets>that</ets>. ⟦root⟧184. See <er>That</er>, <pos>pron.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>In or at that place.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧[They]
<xex>there</xex> left me and my man, both bound together.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Lord God planted a garden eastward in Eden; and
<qex>there</qex> he put the man whom he had formed.</q> <rj><qau>Ge. ii.
8.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In distinction from <xex>here</xex>, <xex>there</xex>
usually signifies a place farther off. ⟦ldquo⟧Darkness <xex>there</xex>
might well seem twilight <xex>here</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Milton.</au></note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In that matter, relation, etc.; at that point,
stage, etc., regarded as a distinct place; <as>as, he did not stop
<ex>there</ex>, but continued his speech</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The law that theaten'd death becomes thy friend⟦br⟧
And turns it to exile; <qex>there</qex> art thou happy.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To or into that place; thither.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The rarest that e'er came <qex>there</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <ex>There</ex> is sometimes used by way of exclamation,
calling the attention to something, especially to something distant; as,
<ex>there</ex>, <ex>there</ex>! see <ex>there</ex>! look <ex>there</ex>!
<ex>There</ex> is often used as an expletive, and in this use, when it
introduces a sentence or clause, the verb precedes its
subject.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A knight <qex>there</qex> was, and that a worthy man.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>There</qex> is a path which no fowl knoweth.</q> <rj><qau>Job
xxviii. 7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wherever <qex>there</qex> is a sense or perception,
<qex>there</qex> some idea is actually produced.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>There</qex> have been that have delivered themselves from
their ills by their good fortune or virtue.</q>
<rj><qau>Suckling.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>There</xex> is much used in composition, and often
has the sense of a pronoun. See <er>Thereabout</er>,
<er>Thereafter</er>, <er>Therefrom</er>, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>There</xex> was formerly used in the sense of
<xex>where</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Spend their good <qex>there</qex> it is reasonable.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Here and there</b></col>, <cd>in one place and
another.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Thither</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thereabouts</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Thereabout</ent>⟦br⟧
